segments.text: I want to be a petroleum engineer.
And it hurt that you go there and you don't have a problem getting a job.
And so... What did you know?
How did you know A&M existed?
What was your information about A&M?
There really wasn't that many people in Rockwall.
There was...
When I got there in 51, there was one person I knew who was a senior vet medicine student from Rockwall.
And, of course, I talked to him, and also I talked to the guy or two that had gone down to the University of Texas, and they were taking something else.
But they advised me that it really ought to be going to Petroleum Engineering.
That was where all the jobs and everybody was doing real well at major teams.
So, there really, at that time, there really weren't that, there wasn't that strong a hold, and it wasn't very big.
At the time, it was 1,499 people, very small school, and a small estate, small county estate.
Let's see, I should put this on, since I didn't have it turned on when I asked you that first question about why did you go.
This is the 18th of June, Thursday afternoon.
We're in Fort Worth, talking to Charlie Sealy.
Did you visit the campus before you went down to enroll?
Yes.
And what was your impression?
Oh, I loved it.
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
This would have been in the...
on the spring of 51 and the MSC had just been built and what a spectacular place it was.
What was their living?
That building, but were there some, were there something that they did or didn't do?
Were there people?
What impression did you get?
Well, I got the impression then just like you do now.
It's a very friendly campus.
Were you there for an official kind of orientation visit, or did you just go?
I don't think they had the orientation type things then.
They're taking the entrance test or something.
Was this with mom and dad?
Yes.
Are you a first generation college student?
Yes.
All right, now let's move forward to the fall.
How did you get there, and what did you take with you?
I've heard of several people that give this same type of thing, and I swear to goodness, it's just almost the same.
It's a mom and dad take them down and let them out, and there you are all of a sudden with a footlocker and a few clothes and almost no money, and you're left.
That's the way it happened.
No car.
And no friends.
Was there anybody that kind of took charge and helped you?
How did you get to a room that night?
How did you get to the Dunning Hall?
How did you know where those places were?
Well, of course, back then, of course, we were in Munich.
And once I finally found the dorm,
I don't remember exactly how, but once I found the dormer, it wasn't much of a problem then on.
So what unit were you in?
I was in squadron five in dorm 15.
This is when we still had the freshman area.
And all the freshmen were together with two or three seniors, a couple of juniors, and two or three sophomores.
But all freshmen were back on the main campus
Nobody was out at O'Brien Air Force Base.
No, that's right.
And did your squadron have a nickname?
No.
No, but we were one about everything.
Do you know how you happened to end up in that squadron instead of some other?
I don't think there was.
At least I didn't know.
I think you could probably do it now.
But I didn't know about it.
Because, like with the Army, you had
field artillery and this and this, but the Air Force was just all.
And y'all were living, was it a whole, was it all a fish dorm?
Yes.
Describe your room as a freshman.
What was in, you and your roommate, what was in that room?
The same thing that's in there now.
Same old dorms.
I'm sure that dorm's still there.
Two beds, two tables, two chairs, a sink, two closets, that's it.
Two bulletin boards.
Was your roommate, did he become a special friend?
Your official lady?
Well, this was a little unusual.
When I got there, I ended up, at the time,
They had a very big class and they were short on room space.
As a result, they had to tie a third bed bunk and put a third person in there.
Well, I think I must have been in the middle because I had two roommates, both of which I really couldn't pronounce their name and I couldn't understand them.
Fish on, I was off the hook and Fish would eat him.
who we really became good friends later.
But I did and was able to let them stay together and move out just to a single person.
And his name was Edwin Dean Bubba Bennett, who later drowned at summer camp his junior year.
So I understand what Silvertown's old campus is like.
Let's see, describe the campus when you were, what buildings were there and where were they when you were a fish?
Okay, being in basic engineering, which is generally what they do, most of the classes were in the academic and faculty hall.
Is faculty still there?
Let's see, I think I might have had a basic course over in the geology building.
I think maybe, of course, I had chemistry over in the chemistry building.
And then maybe a basic course over in what I think was the old Aggieland Inn, which is just across from Sosa Vista.
and all the meals were excellent.
Describe how fish were treated your freshman year.
Give me an example.
If you see anything on TV concerning some of the, I guess it was VMI, it's very similar to that.
And yes or no, there's no excuse, sir.
Always in the race.
See, for a client, particularly one that's in the unit, I always speak to him.
Meals were really...
Kind of an unusual time.
Did you all sit all fish at the same table?
All fish, yes.
Well, no.
We had a couple of classes in each one of the tables.
Only one?
Generally speaking, one.
With all other fish?
All other fish.
Okay, because that's a little different from the routine I've heard others describe.
Well, this back in this time.
No, I know.
That's... All right, so...
Y'all were allowed to, were there any things you were or were not allowed to eat?
Well, of course you didn't get cooked.
Oh, okay.
Unless you answered a question.
Okay.
And you had to know all the descriptions.
Usually one of the questions was the descriptions on the bill and every other ridiculous thing in the world that you can think about and can't think about.
Was there any question that was...
legendary that kind of everybody asked, everybody failed?
Was there any?
I don't know if there was.
I don't remember.
I'm sure there was something that you never could answer.
Yeah, I know what you mean.
Let's see.
Describe a typical weekday routine
from the time y'all got up to the time you went to bed at night?
What happened to when?
Well, the first thing, of course, you'd have a glissom job, blowing the glissom in the dawn.
Waking up, first call, second call, and fall out.
About what time?
I want to think it was 6.30, as soon as possible.
I think we'd get down, fall out about 7, and then we'd have to be in class at 8.
Then, of course, they'd tell you what uniform to wear, if it's raining or whatever.
Of course, we wore the uniform every day.
But then we had to fall out and hold inspection.
And then walk to chapel.
And you all ate in?
In Subesa.
In Subesa, yeah.
And then after that, walk back, clean up the room.
night class, whatever the classes are, come back, fall out for chow again, and barf for chow again.
and classes and labs and whatever it is you need to do.
That would normally be up until about 5 o'clock, and then at 5, you know, you could do even flight football or different things like that.
In many cases, when the company bull rings, you have to go out and walk for hours on end.
Not necessarily food.
It would just be a company thing.
It wouldn't be reported to, at that time, Ross Hall.
In the evenings, after supper, what was the routine?
I think we got back up about 7.30.
We'd have CQ until about 10 o'clock.
As a freshman and as a sophomore, at least 60 points on the floor.
Four on the chair and you're three feet.
And if you had the other restroom or anything like that, you'd have to put a pass on your name tag out on the outside of the door.
Then there'd be lights out at about 10, 30, something like that.
Give me examples from any of your years of some good little tricks, jokes, pranks that you knew about, whether you were involved in them or not.
Do you remember the old water tower?
It's a long way up.
I guess this was my sophomore year.
I stayed over the freshman.
I stayed over the first semester of my sophomore year, freshman year and sophomore year.
I remember getting a couple of freshmen, my roommate, going up on the Yard Tower and facing the ball there on top of that thing.
The Air Force Blue.
I don't remember, but I know this.
It took off some paint, and there must have been 20 or 30 coats of paint on that ball.
All different coats.
You were not the first, were you?
No.
A lot of red.
Where did y'all get the paint?
Gee, you know, I really don't know.
And what hours of the night did y'all go up there?
Oh, it must have been probably one o'clock or something like that.
How long would it take to go from ground up?
How long was the climb?
Well, I don't think it was that long, except he was pretty far.
He was kind of where he had.
It would probably be 20 minutes from the time he was on the ground.
And this is after 1030?
No, this is after 1030.
And so it was the very top of the water tower that was painted?
No, just the bottom.
That's right.
Okay.
And how did you all secure yourselves as you were on the very top painting?
Well, all four of us couldn't get out there.
Thank goodness.
So I was up at the top of the edge.
I was getting one fresh one that made it out there and did the painting.
So on each other's shoulders and that sort of thing?
No, no, no.
There's a ladder that goes up.
There's a ladder on top of it.
So you have a ladder to go on.
It's still a little spooky out there.
About how many nights did it take?
Just one night.
Oh, one night.
No, it's just a big ball.
It's probably 24 inches.
And how long, do you remember how long it was before somebody else's group went up there and painted it a different color?
I don't think it took too long.
Oh.
McCabe probably had artillery red.
All right, do you remember any pranks, a good blow on somebody?
Well, let me tell you this one.
This is pretty different.
I had a pretty fancy roommate as a sophomore there.
I just followed along with the manager.
But we went over to Memorial Stadium and we had two carloads, two sophomores and a freshman.
It was moving in the fall of 50, early September, October of 52.
And at that time, we were going to the grass field.
And by the time we got there, it must have been 2 or 3 o'clock in the morning.
And we took some oats.
It's spelled out.
And of course I'm 55, 56 for the freshmen that did a lot of work.
And went out and talked it in real well.
I'll have to say it looked pretty good on Thanksgiving Day on national television.
That's great.
That's great.
How many participated in that?
Well, there's two cars, so I'm guessing probably about 10.
And nobody got caught, no hint, no anything?
No.
All right.
But they came back the next year.
But they weren't quite as smart as we were, because ours showed up so well.
We probably had letters that were maybe 20 yards or so tall.
They went all the way across Kyle Field.
But it was right on a yard line.
So it really didn't show up in the U.
It was the same way.
It made it square.
So it really didn't show up nearly as dramatic as they are today.
Now, was it known on campus who had done this?
I don't know that anybody knows.
So y'all kept it a secret for a long time.
Oh, OK. All right, what about some pranks played on somebody on the campus?
Some upperclassmen that y'all didn't like?
We had all kinds of different things going on.
I mean, let me think about that just a minute.
Like, surely y'all stole a footlocker every now and then.
I mean, hit a footlocker.
Well, of course, the big thing back then was drowning out the whole dorm.
And, boy, you end up doing that.
I mean, getting bothered.
They take the head off of one of the colognes.
And they just do it on the top floor.
I do remember waking up.
In the middle of the night, I probably hadn't been there in months.
It was fresh water.
The water was just going everywhere.
Coming down the steps, it looked like a, I mean, it looked like a waterfall.
Everybody's out there, you know, in the middle of the night, sweeping water.
It seemed like it took until daylight just about to finally get all the water swept out of it on.
I knew they weren't good.
Let's go the other way.
Did you lock your room door?
Normally during the day or night?
I don't think we did.
Did you ever have anything stolen?
No.
Do you remember anybody that did?
No.
I don't think we ever had anything stolen.
Let's see, did you all ever roll anything under anybody's door with any kind of explosive inside it?
No, but I'll tell you, we did have a guy who we had our own radio station.
It's watered by.
Oh, tell them about that.
The guy's name was Charlie Parker, who actually went into radio, I think, after that.
And he really had quite a show.
He played music and so forth.
The whole dawn would be listening to him instead of the regular radio.
Did he have an identification, call letters or anything?
No, I don't think so.
And it was just so weak.
The FCC did not know that.
The FCC did not know that.
That's correct.
But you all didn't have any Babel bombs?
I remember...
No, really, I don't remember that.
Alright, what about nicknames for food and beverages in the chow hall?
Oh, they're the same as they always were.
Share them with me.
Well, bread, you know, gunwale, bullock, lube for gravy.
Milk, tea?
Cow, you know.
I don't remember what tea it was.
Was that horse?
Beans?
Gas?
Was that beans?
But anyway, it was there.
And were all desserts Cush?
All of them were Cush.
Let's see, how did you dress for class?
Always in a uniform.
What about men?
I never went to a class before, I don't know, all four years, I didn't have a uniform.
And normally, you either had the choice of being in the, at that time, the fatigues were not capitalized, they were good.
And so either you wore a uniform.
And we really didn't have combat boots.
Either you wore your fatigue with a cap or your normal either green or pink shredder in the wintertime or khaki in the summer.
A while ago I thought of a question that I haven't asked anybody else.
Do you remember your first fish haircut?
Oh, yeah.
Where'd you get it?
I was at MSC downstairs.
I thought it was ruined forever.
What did it look like when you looked in the mirror?
There wasn't much hair.
I mean, it was just flat on top.
Do you remember whether it took long for him to do it?
No, no, I didn't think it took long.
Did a group of you fish go together?
Yeah, I recall we had about five or six officers waiting for the last minute that you had to.
And let's see, was there any other nomenclature involved other than a fish haircut, white sidewalls?
Was that a part of the nickname for it?
For the haircut?
No.
So it was just a fish haircut.
All right.
Describe then how your life was different as a sophomore.
A little, a little of what I told you about in the sophomore year.
But at least, as you well know, the only friend that you have on the campus in the school, or your fish buddy, or your sophomore buddy, or your junior buddy, whoever it is,
It's certainly not the upper-class one or the lower-class one.
So as a sophomore in St. Lyons, I didn't particularly enjoy being in the freshman area as a sophomore.
That really wasn't why I wanted to go.
The second semester I ended up going on over to
Yeah, the freshman area and also the core area, I guess, the new area, as you call it.
Yeah, I lived over there the second semester.
It's part of 10th, which is the, back then it was the smart spot.
So you were, you know, over in the Duncan dining hall.
Yes.
Was there anything different about eating, dining in Duncan compared to Sabeasa?
I think so.
I think the food is about the same.
They kind of did it the same way and so forth.
Only this time we have seniors, juniors, and a lot more.
In hindsight, describe Aggie food.
Well, I thought it was good.
A lot of the other people didn't necessarily like it, but gee, compared to
being growing up on a farm and when we had beans, you know, different types of beans, at least four or five days a week.
Those ready pork chops and things weren't that bad.
Do you remember what it cost your semester or year?
I think, if I'm not mistaken, the room and the board caused it.
Everything was about $250 a semester.
That was everything.
Did you have a job ever on campus?
No, but I worked very intensely all during the summer.
What did you do?
What kind of jobs did you have?
Different things.
Construction for a couple of years there.
Oil field for one year and then the next year.
The summer camp, which I had spent time working at the aluminum factory.
So were you able to earn enough in the summers to pretty well pay your bill?
Pretty close.
Pretty close.
About how much money did you spend, let's say free spending money?
None.
But, you know, the last two years, if you sign a contract, then they pay you about $30 a month or something like that.
I think it's about $100.
It wasn't a lot.
Boy, we thought it was marvelous at the time.
Well, I didn't have a car.
So if I left at all, I didn't hitchhike.
Back then, there wasn't a problem at all.
We had the line, which was... Now, where would that line be?
Where did you go to catch the line from?
From, say, Bryan to St. Alex 4.
It was down just on the north side of, I guess it's Highway 6.
Very important.
All right, so you went downtown Bryan to... All right, now how'd you get from campus down there?
I can't tell you.
I do not remember.
I'm sure I probably just been driving through.
Somebody just got a ride with someone.
There were no cars going back and forth.
In Rockwall, where did you get off?
It wasn't really easy, but there was a place in Downs where you'd have to go down.
And it was on Highway 75.
I wouldn't go there now.
It'd really be right in the south area.
I don't think it was right there.
And you came down Highway 75 to Madisonville?
Actually, no.
He turned off at...
Turned off at Richland, south of Corsicana?
That's correct.
Okay.
And go to Bahia.
And then to Bahia to have a party.
Did you ever have any unusual hitchhiking experiences that you can share?
There are.
There are.
I don't know how you live through those.
One time I was in Houston.
the day that I ended up married.
We had gone together in high school.
Her father was the principal of the school at Rockwell.
We ended up moving to Paulsville, just east of Longview.
For some reason, I thought, it was my freshman year, I thought I had to go see her.
I hitchhiked from Houston all the way to Longview to Paulsville and then back.

I think I might have had a riot back, but getting up there and going through some of the East Texas oil fields with this roughneck who was absolutely, had been working day and night and couldn't stay awake.
I really didn't know whether we were going to make it or not.
And then one time coming back from Houston, I can remember for some reason in a uniform,
attracted maybe some of the most undesirable people.
And I ended up getting out of the car at Hempstead to catch another accident.
You know, I didn't think anything at all about Hempstead.
Did you ever hear of any of your friends having any truly bad... Not a real problem.
Nobody shared one of those with me yet?
All right, now let's do some academics.
As you think back on it, who were some of the, for you, who were some of the important teachers and or advisors, counselors?
